ten, courts impose their own stereotyped view of how women and men “ought” to behave in the workplace. This viewpoint, social science reveals, is frequently out of sync with reality.As a legal scholar who takes social science seriously, Beiner provides valuable insight into what behaviors people perceive as sexually harassing, why such behavior can be characterized as discrimination because of sex, and what types of workplaces are more conducive to sexually harassing behavior than others. Throughout, Beiner offers proposals for legal reform with the goal of furthering workplace equality for both men and women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLaw and the social scienceszUnited States. 0aSexual harassmentxLaw and legislationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh  aBeiner.  abecause.  abehavior.  abehaviors.  acharacterized.  aconducive.  adiscrimination.  aharassing.  ainsight.  ainto.  alegal.  amore.  aothers.  apeople.  aperceive.  aprovides.  ascholar.  ascience.  aseriously.  asex.  asexually.  asocial.  asuch.  atakes.  athan.  atypes.  avaluable.  awhat.  aworkplaces.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814739426.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK